{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_18","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"jq -r 'select(.type==\\\"item.completed\\\" and .item.type==\\\"agent_message\\\") | .item.text' human-intervention-logs/org.apache.lucene:lucene-core:5.0.0/metadata-fix/codex.log\"","aggregated_output":"I’m using the `fix-missing-reachability-metadata` skill because this is a targeted metadata repair for a specific library version. I’ll first inspect the existing Lucene entries and the skill workflow, then reproduce the failure with the exact GraalVM you specified.\nI have the relevant Lucene 5.0.0 metadata and tests in place. Next I’m validating the exact GraalVM binary path and reproducing the `org.apache.lucene:lucene-core:5.0.0` failure under that environment before editing anything.\nThe required GraalVM is present and I’ve confirmed the commands are resolving to the exact installation you specified. Its `native-image --version` in this valid worktree prints `Oracle GraalVM 25.1.0-dev+10.1`, so I’m moving on to the actual Lucene 5.0.0 reproduction now.\nGradle is running under the pinned GraalVM now. I’m waiting for the first native-image/test failure so I can patch the precise missing registrations instead of guessing from nearby Lucene versions.\nThe shipped Lucene 5.0.0 test already passes under the pinned GraalVM, so the problem is not a straightforward missing-registration failure in the current baseline. I’m checking the metadata file itself against adjacent versions and the test-local metadata now to find the actual inconsistency that needs correction.\nThe current tree still validates and tests cleanly, so this looks more like a metadata-quality issue than a broken build. I’m searching the worktree for task context and comparing Lucene 5.0.0 against neighboring versions to identify the entry set that should actually be normalized.\nI found that Lucene 5.0.0’s shipped metadata diverges from every later 5.x version, but the current test suite still happens to pass. I’m checking branch history and the generated metadata/test coverage record now so I can distinguish “stale but harmless” from “actually wrong for the native run this branch is meant to fix.”\nI found one concrete reason for the 5.0.0 drift: its test suite still exercises an older `RamUsageEstimator` initialization path than 5.1.0+, so some extra entries are test-driven rather than obviously wrong. I’m checking the Lucene 5.0.0 source itself now to separate real library requirements from stale metadata carried over by generation.\nThe Lucene 5.0.0 and 5.1.0 code genuinely differs, so I’m not going to blindly copy later metadata over. One suspicious area remains: the 5.0.0 `MMapDirectory` conditions point at `$1$1`, but the bytecode suggests the reflective cleaner path may actually live under a different anonymous class, so I’m drilling into those inner classes next.\nThe code and current tests still don’t expose a hard failure, so I’m pulling the branch/PR context from GitHub next. If there’s an existing native-image failure report behind this worktree, that will tell me which metadata entry is actually expected to change.\nI found the real reproducer: this is not a missing-registration failure. Under `GVM_TCK_NATIVE_IMAGE_MODE=future-defaults-all`, Lucene 5.0.0 fails two `SPIClassIteratorTest` assertions in native runtime, so I’m reproducing that exact mode locally with the pinned GraalVM and then I’ll adjust the metadata/resources around SPI loading.\nI have enough context to make a narrow metadata repair. I’m adding the missing `java.lang.management.ManagementFactory#getPlatformMXBean(Class)` registration for `RamUsageEstimator`, because Lucene 5.0.0 invokes that method reflectively in its static initializer and the 5.0.0 metadata file currently skips that step.\nThe edit is in. I’m re-running the exact GraalVM version check and then validating the Lucene 5.0.0 metadata file plus the `future-defaults-all` native test path under that same distribution.\nThe metadata file validates. I’m running the stronger verification now: `clean test` for `org.apache.lucene:lucene-core:5.0.0` with `GVM_TCK_NATIVE_IMAGE_MODE=future-defaults-all` under the exact pinned GraalVM, since that was the failing mode in the automation issue.\nThe actual metadata change is isolated to the Lucene 5.0.0 metadata JSON. My verification run also touched the checked-in native test-result snapshots, so I’m restoring those generated files back to their original contents before I finish.\nUpdated [reachability-metadata.json](/home/jovan/Work/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/forge_worktrees/7343-b6daa1c8/metadata/org.apache.lucene/lucene-core/5.0.0/reachability-metadata.json:113) for `org.apache.lucene:lucene-core:5.0.0` by adding the missing reflective registration for `java.lang.management.ManagementFactory#getPlatformMXBean(Class)` under the `org.apache.lucene.util.RamUsageEstimator` condition.\n\nVerification used only the required GraalVM at `/home/jovan/ol/bb/master/graal/sdk/mxbuild/linux-amd64/GRAALVM_JAVA25/graalvm-25.1.0-dev+10.1`. `native-image --version` resolved to `Oracle GraalVM 25.1.0-dev+10.1`, `./gradlew checkMetadataFiles -Pcoordinates=org.apache.lucene:lucene-core:5.0.0 --stacktrace` passed, and `GVM_TCK_LV=5.0.0 GVM_TCK_NATIVE_IMAGE_MODE=future-defaults-all ./gradlew clean test -Pcoordinates=org.apache.lucene:lucene-core:5.0.0 --stacktrace` also passed.\n\nThe previously reported native runtime failure from the automation issue did not reproduce on this exact `25.1.0-dev+10.1` build, but the metadata is now complete for that reflective path.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
